>I've got a Canadian model, that I'm about to import into TX.  It's been 
>here
>four years.  I drove it down and couldn't import it because VWOA gave me a
>wrong letter to give to customs that said my van didn't comply with
>emissions (US std. 1978 vs. Canada): spelt not worth the $thousands to have
>a registered importer upgrade it.
>
>While I fought VWOA over the mistake to get the correct letter, my van sat
>in the driveway and I lost interested in going through the whole importing
>procedure (change speedo, etc).  In that time the gas tank turned into
>sludge.
>
>I finally built up the courage to clean out the gas tank; the van is 
>running
>now and I'm about to change the speedo.
>
>My van is labelled non-catalyst so it's probably equivalent to a FED model
>and I'm planning to move to CA later this year.  I was curious about your
>experience with the smog police.
>
>I figure that if I tried to import the van directly into CA, I've have a
>host of troubles because it's a FED model and is missing all extra items,
>like filler neck restrictor.  I replaced the filler neck when I cleaned out
>the gas tank because it was starting to tear and it was easier to get to
>while the tank was out.
>
>On 3/27/02 11:39 AM, "Charles Watson" wrote:
>
> > Here is the story. You can't pass CAL smog with a "tampered" fuel filler
> > neck. Now if you or the PO drive away from a pump without removing the 
>fuel
> > nozzle the filler restrictor can be torn and fall under the "tampered"
> > category. This is a eyeball test. Heck technically they could fine you I
> > guess.
> > The restrictor is to keep you from using leaded gas and poisoning the 
>CAT
> > converter ( required for my 77 bus but not required for FED 49 state 77
> > models).
> > My restrictor was torn and only the FED version was available at a
> > reasonable price ~$20. I was quoted $150 if they could find one at SMOG 
>HELP
> > (1-800-544-4357 Darron I believe was his name).
> >
> > I put in the FED version 211 201 199 I think the CAL version is 211 201
> > 199B. Replacing this part CAL or FED is not fun. The smog tech looked 
>into
> > my filler and marked me down for a tampered fuel restrictor (FED 
>version).
> >
> > So here's what I did. I cut the hood off the damaged CAL filler neck, 
>closed
> > the torn restrictor hole by tightening a wire tie around it (it looked
> > good). I left the opening lip attached to the trimmed and closed 
>restrictor.
> > I removed the metal flange from the fuel opening, applied a coat of Vas 
>to
> > the trimmed CAL neck and shoved it into the FED neck. I replaced the 
>flange
> > (4 screws) and passed smog.
> >
> > I warned you it was a long story.
>


